e book |last=Hollinger |first=Karen |title=The Actress: Hollywood Acting and the Female Star |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DcxEAQAAQBAJ&dq |year=2006 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-1352-0588-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Insdorf |first=Annette |title=Indelible Shadows: Film and the Holocaust |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HXrbo7xFJc0C&pg=PA36 |year=2003 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-01630-8 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Kachmar |first=Diane C. |title=Roy Scheider: A Film Biography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A6SmDaC8VXoC&pg=PA95 |date=January 1, 2002 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-0-7864-1201-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Longworth |first=Karina |title=Meryl Streep: Anatomy of an Actor |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dJv1mwEACAAJ |year=2013 |publisher=Phaidon Press |isbn=978-0-7148-6669-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Montalbano |first=Dave |title=The Adventures of Cinema Dave in the Florida Motion Picture World |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hvfExNxOXpsC |date=December 22, 2010 |publisher=Xlibris Corporation |isbn=978-1-4628-3673-4 |ref=harv}}{{Self-published inline|certain=yes|date=December 2017}}\n* {{cite book |last=M\u00fcller |first=J\u00fcrgen |title=Movies of the 80s |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DxIsCgbpdbUC&pg=PA388 |year=2002 |publisher=Taschen |isbn=978-3-8228-1737-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Rice |first=Dona Herweck |title=The 20th Century Series: The Eighties |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oD03pzB3ObcC&pg=PA66 |date=August 1, 1999 |publisher=Teacher Created Resources |isbn=978-1-57690-030-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Santas |first=Constantine |title=Responding to Film |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mcbj95l1zmUC&dq=Responding+to+Film |year=2002 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-0-8304-1580-9 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Wolcott |first=James |title=Smitten Kittens |journal=Texas Monthly |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WywEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA173 |date= October 1981 |publisher=Emmis Communications |issn=0148-7736 |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|658|name=Meryl Streep}}\n* {{tcmdb name|185873|name=Meryl Streep}}\n* {{IBDB name|61324|name=Meryl Streep}}\n\n{{featured list}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Streep, Meryl filmography}}\n[[Category:Actress filmographies]]\n[[Category:American filmographies]]\n[[Category:Meryl Streep]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|List of performances by Meryl Streep}}\n[[File:Meryl Streep by Jack Mitchell.jpg|thumb|alt=A headshot of Meryl Streep in the 1970s with her facing the camera with her right arm propping her head up|[[Meryl Streep]] in the late 1970s]]\n[[Meryl Streep]] is an American actress who has had an extensive career in film, television, and stage.{{sfn|Santas|2002|pp=187}}{{sfn|Hollinger|2006|pp=94\u201395}} She made her stage debut in 1975 with [[The Public Theater]] production of ''[[Trelawny of the 'Wells']]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fung|first=Lisa|title=Meryl Streep Donates $1M to New York\u2019s Public Theater|url=https://www.thewrap.com/meryl-streep-donates-1m-new-yorks-public-theater-59371/|publisher=[[TheWrap]]|date=October 4, 2012|accessdate=May 5, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505103322/http://www.thewrap.com/meryl-streep-donates-1m-new-yorks-public-theater-59371/|archivedate=May 5, 2015}}</ref> She went on to perform several roles on stage in the 1970s, garnering a [[Tony Award]] nomination for her role in ''[[One act plays by Tennessee Williams#27 Wagons Full of Cotton|27 Wagons Full of Cotton]]'' (1976).<ref name=AFI>{{cite web|author1=Levy, Rochelle L.|title=2004 Meryl Streep Tribute|url=http://www.afi.com/laa/laa04.aspx|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|accessdate=January 20, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221094149/http://www.afi.com/laa/laa04.aspx|archivedate=February 21, 2015}}</ref> In 1977, Streep starred in the television movie ''[[The Deadliest Season]]'', and made her film debut with a brief role alongside [[Jane Fonda]] in ''[[Julia (1977 film)|Julia]]''.{{sfn|Longworth|2013|pp=10}} A supporting role in the war drama ''[[The Deer Hunter]]'' (1978) proved to be a breakthrough for Streep; she received her first [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Academy Award]] nomination for it.{{sfn|Longworth|2013|pp=32}} She won the award the following year for playing a troubled wife in the top-grossing drama ''[[Kramer vs. Kramer]]'' (1979).<ref>{{cite web|last=Sternbergh|first=Adam|title=Why Was Kramer vs. Kramer the Top-Grossing Movie of 1979?|url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/10/how-did-kramer-vs-kramer-make-so-much-money.html|publisher=Vulture|date=October 3, 2014|accessdate=May 5, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505095344/http://www.vulture.com/2014/10/how-did-kramer-vs-kramer-make-so-much-money.html|archivedate=May 5, 2015}}</ref> Also in 1978, Streep played a German woman married to a Jewish man in [[Nazi Germany]] in the television miniseries ''[[Holocaust (miniseries)|Holocaust]]'', which earned her the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie|Emmy Award for Best Actress]].{{sfn|M\u00fcller|2002|pp=131}}\n\nStreep established herself as a leading Hollywood actress in the 1980s.{{sfn|Longworth|2013|pp=49}}<ref name=\"fame\">{{cite news|last=Siskel|first=Gene|title=Streep likes fame, avoids stardom|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19811010&id=8noxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=zaQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3898,4737430&hl=en|work=[[Montreal Gazette]]|date=October 10, 1981|accessdate=May 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403193818/https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19811010&id=8noxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=zaQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3898,4737430&hl=en|archive-date=April 3, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> She played dual roles in the period drama ''[[The French Lieutenant's Woman (film)|The French Lieutenant's Woman]]'' (1981),<ref name=\"fame\"/> and starred as a Polish Holocaust survivor in ''[[Sophie's Choice (film)|Sophie's Choice]]'' (1982).{{sfn|Insdorf|2003|pp=35\u201336}} She was awarded the [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress Oscar]] for the latter.{{sfn|M\u00fcller|2002|pp=131}} Streep portrayed the real-life character of [[Karen Silkwood]] in [[Mike Nichols]]' drama ''[[Silkwood]]'' (1983),{{sfn|Rice|1999|pp=66}} before starring in her most financially successful release of the decade, the romantic drama ''[[Out of Africa (film)|Out of Africa]]'' (1985), in which she played the Danish writer [[Karen Blixen]].{{sfn|Hollinger|2006|pp=388}}<ref name=\"boxoffice\">{{cite web|title=Meryl Streep Movie Box Office Results|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Actor&id=merylstreep.htm&sort=rank&order=ASC&p=.htm|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=May 5, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505095423/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Actor&id=merylstreep.htm&sort=rank&order=ASC&p=.htm|archivedate=May 5, 2015}}</ref> Despite intermittent successes, Streep's career went through a period of decline post-1985, with several commentators criticizing her for her inclination towards melodramatic roles.{{sfn|Hollinger|2006|pp=78\u201379}} The criticism continued despite her attempts to actively star in commercial comedies, films that parodied women's beauty and aging, ''[[She-Devil]]'' (1989) and ''[[Death Becomes Her]]'' (1992).{{sfn|Longworth|2013|pp=97}}\n\nIn 1995, Streep starred opposite [[Clint Eastwood]] as an unhappily married woman in ''[[The Bridges of Madison County (film)|The Bridges of Madison County]]'', her biggest critical and commercial success of the decade.<ref name=\"boxoffice\"/>{{sfn|Longworth|2013|pp=110\u2013125}} Although her dramas of the late 1990s received a mixed reception overall,<ref>{{cite web|last=Ebert|first=Roger|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/before-and-after-1996|title=Before and After (1996)|publisher=RogerEbert.com|date=February 23, 1996|accessdate=May 5, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511060211/http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/before-and-after-1996|archivedate=May 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Maslin, Janet|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B04E3DA1431F930A25752C1A96E958260|title=Movie Review of Dancing at Lughnasa|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 13, 1998|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref> she was praised for her role as a cancer patient in ''[[One True Thing]]'' (1998).<ref name=\"LaSalle\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/1998/09/18/DD59798.DTL|title=Home Is a Beautiful `Thing' / Streep shines in drama about ailing mother|last=LaSalle|first=Mick|date=September 18, 1998|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate=June 6, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090413162840/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fc%2Fa%2F1998%2F09%2F18%2FDD59798.DTL|archivedate=April 13, 2009}}</ref> She had acclaimed roles in the 2002 films ''[[Adaptation (film)|Adaptation.]]'' and ''[[The Hours (film)|The Hours]]'', and won a second Emmy Award for the television miniseries ''[[Angels in America (miniseries)|Angels in America]]'' a year later, though she failed to replicate her earlier success.{{sfn|Longworth|2013|pp=127}}<ref name=\"angels\">{{cite news|last=Weinraub|first=Bernard|title=HBO Is Big Winner at Emmy Awards|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/09/20/arts/television/20emmy.html?pagewanted=print&position=|date=September 20, 2004|work=The New York Times|accessdate=May 5, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528061553/http://www.nytimes.com/2004/09/20/arts/television/20emmy.html?pagewanted=print&position=|archivedate=May 28, 2015}}</ref> This changed in 2006, with an Academy Award-nominated role as a ruthless fashion magazine editor in the comedy-drama ''[[The Devil Wears Prada (film)|The Devil Wears Prada]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wloszczyna|first=Susan|title=The 3 Acts of Meryl Streep's Long and Glorious Career|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/the-3-acts-of-meryl-streeps-long-and-glorious-career-20150121|publisher=[[Indiewire]]|date=January 21, 2015|accessdate=May 5, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401051042/http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/the-3-acts-of-meryl-streeps-long-and-glorious-career-20150121#|archivedate=2015-04-01}}</ref> This late-period success led to starring roles in several high-profile films, including the US$609 million-grossing romantic comedy ''[[Mamma Mia! (film)|Mamma Mia!]]'' (2008), her highest-grossing release, and the comedy-drama ''[[Julie & Julia]]'' (2009), in which she played [[Julia Child]].{{sfn|Longworth|2013|pp=141\u2013142}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Mamma Mia! (2008)|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=mammamia.htm|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=May 5, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102050129/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=mammamia.htm|archivedate=January 2, 2010}}</ref> These roles re-established Streep's stardom in Hollywood.<ref>{{cite news|last=Scott|first=A.O.|title=That Unmistakable Streepness|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/21/movies/awardsseason/21scott.html?_r=0|date=February 18, 2010|work=The New York Times|accessdate=May 5, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150519024125/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/21/movies/awardsseason/21scott.html?_r=0|archivedate=May 19, 2015}}</ref> Her portrayal of [[Margaret Thatcher]] in the biopic ''[[The Iron Lady (film)|The Iron Lady]]'' (2011) earned her another Academy Award for Best Actress.<ref>{{cite news|last=Perlman|first=Jake|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/02/26/2012-oscar-winners/|title=Oscars winners list: 'The Artist,' Jean Dujardin, and Meryl Streep take home top awards|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=February 26, 2012|accessdate=April 20, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140216081922/http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/02/26/2012-oscar-winners/|archivedate=February 16, 2014}}</ref> The starring role of [[Katharine Graham]] in the 2017 drama ''[[The Post (film)|The Post]]'' garnered Streep her 21st Oscar nomination, more than any actor or actress in history.<ref>{{cite news|last=McNary|first=Dave|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/meryl-streep-oscar-nominations-record-the-post-1202673327/|title=Meryl Streep Breaks Own Record With 21st Oscar Nomination|work=Variety|date=January 23, 2018|accessdate=January 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123232451/http://variety.com/2018/film/news/meryl-streep-oscar-nominations-record-the-post-1202673327/|archive-date=January 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Film==\n[[File:Meryl Streep - Berlin Berlinale 66 (24976691665) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Streep at the [[66th Berlin International Film Festival]] in 2016]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| {{dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n!scope=\"col\"| Year\n!scope=\"col\"| Title\n!scope=\"col\"| Role\n!scope=\"col\"| Director(s)\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|1977\n!scope=row| ''[[Julia (1977 film)|Julia]]''\n| {{sortname|Anne|Marie|nolink=yes}}\n| {{sortname|Fred|Zinnemann}}\n|\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"| {{sfn|Dick|1982|pp=178}}\n|-\n|1978\n!scope=row| ''{{sort|deer|[[The Deer Hunter]]}}''\n| Linda\n| {{sortname|Michael|Cimino}}\n|\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"| {{sfn|Longworth|2013|pp=18\u201333}}\n|-\n|1979\n!scope=row|''[[Manhattan (1979 film)|Manhattan]]''\n| Jill\n| {{sortname|Woody|Allen}}\n|\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"| {{sfn|Darren|2000|pp=141}}\n|